Photo by History Uncovered in Rome, Italy. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'Sewer Workers Just Happened Upon A 2,000-Year-Old Stone That Once Marked The City Limits Of Ancient Rome'.

node.text:
Excavations for a new sewer system just revealed a giant stone slab that once marked the city limits of ancient Rome. Made of travertine limestone, the stone was discovered at the newly-restored Mausoleum of Augustus, just off the Via del Corso, the main thoroughfare in Rome's historic city center. ⁠
⁠
Ancient Rome had strict rules about who could cross the boundary into the capital city proper, as well as what activities could be performed within the limits. Provincial promagistrates, generals, and soldiers were forbidden from entering the city unless they resigned their authority upon crossing the line. Citizens were barred from building, living, or farming along the border area. It was forbidden to bury any deceased within the city walls. Even elected magistrates ceded some of their power within the city limits, where they lost the legal right to sentence citizens to death. ⁠
⁠
Go inside this incredible archaeological find by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#rome #ancienthistory #historyofeurope #ancientrome #finds #discoveries #historynews

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Egypt. May be an image of 2 people and sculpture.

node.text:
It was common for ancient Egyptians to favor one god over another, but Queen Nefertiti and Pharaoh Akhenaten consolidated worship under one god: Aten, the god of the sun. Doing so made them controversial leaders and created religious upheaval in the kingdom, but they ruled with unprecedented power because of it.⁠
⁠
Some historians even believe that Queen Nefertiti ruled with equal power to her husband — and that when he died, she disguised herself as a man in order to take his place. Discover the mysterious story of Queen Nefertiti by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#worldhistory #historyofegypt #queennefertiti #ancienthistory

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on August 02, 2021.

node.text:
Artifacts as much as 4,000 years old show that the ancient Egyptians were practicing dentistry that remains astounding even today. They had toothpaste made of ingredients like rock salt and pepper while their cavity fillings were made of linen dipped in fig juice.⁠
⁠
From ancient sex toys to Roman wine, see the most astounding artifacts of antiquity by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#ancienthistory #ancientegypt #dentalwork #whoa #historical

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Detroit, Michigan. May be a black-and-white image of 2 people.

node.text:
"He just wiped the blood off the flashlight and put it back where he had it."⁠
⁠
On November 5, 1992, Malice Green had just driven a friend back to his home on Detroit's west side when a pair of plainclothes police officers approached his car. In their telling, Green had pulled into a known crack house and the officers claimed Green was holding something in his hand that he refused to drop.⁠
⁠
What ensued was a brutal beating by flashlight, with up to 14 lacerating blows landing on his head, killing him. Green had neither crack nor a weapon. Go inside this lesser-known story of police brutality in Detroit by clicking the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
⁠
#malicegreen #ushistory #policebrutality #detroit #historyofdetroit #1992

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on August 01, 2021. May be an image of 3 people and people standing.

node.text:
Soon after Jimmy Carter became president, he got a call from his friend Elvis Presley. "He was totally stoned and didn't know what he was saying," Carter later recalled. "His sentences were almost incoherent."⁠
⁠
He wanted the president to pardon a friend of his who was a sheriff and experiencing legal trouble. "I asked him what the sheriff's sentence was, and he said that he hadn’t been tried in court yet. Well, I said, 'Elvis, I can't consider a pardon until after a trial and sentencing and everything.' I don’t think he understood that," said Carter.⁠
⁠
The King Of Rock continued to call, but Carter stopped answering. Later that summer, Elvis died of a drug overdose at the age of 42. Learn more little-known facts about Jimmy Carter by visiting the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
#jimmycarter #presidentcarter #elvispresley #elvis #weirdfacts

node.text:
Meet Cú Chulainn, the incredible hulk of Irish folklore who became a symbol of Irish nationalism. Half-man, half-god, Cú Chulainn was only 17 when the King of Munster speared him and his bowels spilled onto the cushions of his chariot. But to the King's surprise, the hero simply gathered his bowels back into his body — and invited his enemies to continue fighting.⁠
⁠
To learn more about this mythological legend, click the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#cúchulainn #irishfolklore #irishmythology #irishhistory

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on July 31, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Decades Betore Jack The Ripper, This Vicious Victorian Mom Became The First Serial Killer In British History'.

node.text:
In 1872, a British woman named Mary Ann Cotton wanted to get married for the fifth time. But because her last husband had died, she had to take care of his son instead. Then Cotton eerily quipped, "I won't be troubled long" — and the child was soon found dead of arsenic poisoning.⁠
⁠
During their investigation into the child's death, Durham police uncovered a startling pattern in Mary Ann Cotton's life: three of her four husbands and perhaps two of her other lovers had all died under mysterious circumstances while they were with her. Though she maintained her innocence, Cotton was charged with fatally poisoning as many as 21 people — including 11 of her own children.⁠
⁠
Visit the link in our profile for the gruesome true story of Britain's first serial killer.⁠
⁠
⁠
#britishhistory #marycotton #maryanncotton #victorianengland #disturbing #serialkiller

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered on July 30, 2021. May be an image of 2 people and text that says 'Inside The Bizarre Theory That Paul McCartney Died In 1966 And Was Replaced By A Lookalike'.

node.text:
One of the most famous conspiracy theories in rock and roll history is that Paul McCartney secretly died in a car accident in 1966. According to believers, The Beatles' manager Brian Epstein attended a Paul McCartney lookalike contest shortly afterward and selected the winner to become the new Paul McCartney, taking on his voice, playing style, and mannerisms in order to keep The Beatles' machine running. ⁠
⁠
But before the Beatles broke up in 1970, the remaining three band members allegedly left clues scattered in Beatles album art and in song lyrics that tipped their hand to the public and clandestinely announced his death. It has supposedly even been verified by Ringo Starr and George Harrison. Learn more about the "Paul Is Dead" conspiracy theory by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#thebeatles #paulmccartney #paulisdead #strange #weirdhistory #history #weird

node.text:
During the hippie era, it seemed like all roads led to Goa. Those who embarked on the "Hippie Trail" through Asia often ended their trek in India's smallest state — where free love, drugs, and a remarkably inclusive culture led to the birth of the Goa hippie movement.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
While many Americans and Europeans had left Goa by the 1980s, some chose to stick around, preserving the free-and-easy lifestyle that still attracts travelers today. See what Goa looked like back in its hippie heyday by clicking the link in our profile.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
⁠⁠
#goa #hippie #india #tourism #whoa #vintage #photoseries #galleries
